An explainer Jupyter Notebook.

1. Introduction and understanding the data

We decided to analyze the Urban Forest Dataset from the city of Melbourne. We thought it would be interesting because it is something that is very easily overlooked, when walking into a park or down the street. People tend not to appreciate the green eventhough they can have a natural cooling effect and can help fight climate change.

1.2. Dataset size and feature selection

The size of the dataset is 14.8 Mb. There are 74.6K rows, each row representing a tree and 19 columns. The columns we decided to use in our analysis are mostly the’Common Name' of the tree, the ‘Family’ and ‘Genus’ that the tree belongs to , the’Diameter Breast Height', the ‘Date Planted’ and the ‘Located in’ for the machine learning part.

There is geo-data in the dataset (‘Latitude’, ‘Longitude’) that we are planning to use for a heat-map representation. For further geographical analysis we will merge in what city area the trees are planted in from the Australian Postcodes dataset.

2. Data preprocessing and summary statistics

We will now clean the dataset for NaN and undesired values as wel as merge in the area where each tree is planted. Then we will get an overview of how the data is distributed.

3. Random Forest Classification

We will choose the two most frequent families of trees and use the random forest classifier machine learning technique. The classifier will take the diameter at breast height and the year that is was planted and the location it is planted and return the family of the tree.

Diameter at breast height (otherwise known as DBH), is the standard for measuring trees. It refers to the tree diameter measured at 4.5 feet (approximately 1,4 meters) above the ground.

As mentioned earlier, column Diameter Breast Height has high rates of missing values. Because of the volume of the dataset, when dropping the missing values, we still had a large amount of data to train and test our model. (23535 rows)

3.2. Encode the variables

This step is necessary since Random Forest model is unable to read strings or any non-numeric datatypes (Random Forest Classifier in Python). The variable that needs to be encoded is the Location. There are many ways to turn the categorical variables into numeric ones ( for instance the OneHotEncoder from sklearn etc.) but we chose pandas fuction get_dummies for it.( ref: our group’s assignment 2).

Location_onehot = pd.get_dummies(df2['Located in'])
#Location_onehot

# Feature variables
X = pd.concat((Location_onehot, df2['Year']), axis=1)
X.head()

Park Street Year
2 0 1 2006
4 0 1 2006
8 0 1 1997
14 1 0 1999
24 1 0 2009

Instead of encoding the family variable, we just converted it to 0 and 1.

# Target variable
y = np.where(df2['Family'] == 'Myrtaceae', 0, 1)

3.3 Splitting the training and the test set and building the model

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3) # 70% training and 30% test

# Build the model 

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100)

# Train the model using the training dataset

clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

RandomForestClassifier()

3.4. Evaluate the model

Below we selected to evaluate the model we built via the accuracy, the cross validation score and confusion matrix.

# Predict the results for test set

y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)

# accuracy

accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
print(f"The accuracy of the model is {round(accuracy_score(y_test,y_pred),3)*100} %")

The accuracy of the model is 72.1 %

# cross validation score
scores = cross_val_score(clf, X, y, cv=5)
print("%0.2f accuracy with a standard deviation of %0.2f" % (scores.mean(), scores.std()))

0.72 accuracy with a standard deviation of 0.01

# confusion matrix

from sklearn.metrics import plot_confusion_matrix

plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
ax = plt.gca(); 

plot_confusion_matrix(clf, X_test, y_test, ax=ax,cmap = "Greens_r", display_labels=[x.title() for x in families])
plt.show()

The confusion matrix allowed us to visualize the performance of the classifier. It can be seen that the model made 3576 predictions. From those, the model predicted correctly 2259.

3.5. Is the model overfitting?

Overfitting occurs when the model learns the training set very well but is unable to generalize its knowledge to the test set.

# accuracy of training set

y_pred_train = clf.predict(X_train)
accuracy_train=accuracy_score(y_train, y_pred_train)
print(f"The accuracy of the model is {round(accuracy_train,3)*100} %")

The accuracy of the model is 71.5 %

The difference between the accuracies is marginal, so the classifier is not overfitting.

4.Distribution of the tree families per year

The following graph is an interactive visualization of the 14 most common families of trees found in the data set throughout the years of 1997 - 2020.

We found this extremely useful when comparing data, this graph gives you the ability to visualize multiple attributes within the same range in an easy and practical way.

In this graph we are using vertical vars to show the data, although we used vbar() method to assing multiple values to the vertical vars - in this case the different families found in our dataset.

We created an empty figure were we used a variety of parameters.

  • x_range and y_range are used to set the horizontal and vertical dimentions and FactorRange was used to explicitly set the different values we have in Years.
  • plot_width and plot_height are used to set the width and height of a plot.
  • title, x_axis_label and y_axis_label are used to set the title and axis names.
  • toolbar_location is set as None to hide the Bokeh toolbar.

Then we added the bars, set colors and other attributes

  • The colors for each crime are set with viridis color palette.
  • bar = { } to store vbars
  • items = # for the custom legend
  • vbar renders all the vertical bars and has some of the atttibutes we need to make this an interactive plot.
  • alpha is used to show the lines drawn and specify the intensity of them (a float value between 0 and 1)
  • muted_alpha is used to specify that muted lines should be drawn with a low alpha muted glyph.
  • fill_color for the specific color to use.

df5.reset_index(level=0, inplace=True)

df5['Year'] = df5['Year'].astype(str)

years = df5['Year'].astype(str)

source = ColumnDataSource(df5)

legend = Legend(items=items, location="center")
p.add_layout(legend, 'left')
p.legend.label_text_font_size = "12px"
p.legend.click_policy="mute"

Here we positioned the legend on the left, in the center, with a font size of 12 and mutting the glyph by setting the click_policy = “mute”

5. Geographical Visualization

We were curious about the common and not so common trees planted in Melbourne and how they are distributed.

5.1 Geographical Data Visualization

We will now create a visualizations that allow us to quickly evaluate tree distributions. These will be in a form of a heatmap where we can see how many trees have been planted per year. Another visualization will be a barchart that breaks down the genus of the trees based on the five major cities in melbourne.

5.1.1 Distribution Of Trees Per Year With Heatmaps

The advantage of visualizing spatial data with maps is being able to get an overview of the datapoints locations. Thus making it possible to garner geographical insights from the data.
Adding the time aspect to the heatmaps also adds another dimension to the visualization as we can get another overview of the tree planting effort through time.

data2 = data[['CoM ID', 'Family', 'Located in', 'Year', 'Latitude', 'Longitude']].copy()

First, we create a list containing the list of values that we wish to plot, grouped by the dimension that we want to use namely year.

lat_long_list = []
for i in range(1997,2021):
    temp=[]
    for index, instance in data2[data2['Year'] == i].iterrows():
        temp.append([instance['Latitude'],instance['Longitude']])
    lat_long_list.append(temp)

x_mean=data['Longitude'].mean()
y_mean=data['Latitude'].mean()

from folium.plugins import HeatMapWithTime
from branca.element import Figure
fig7=Figure(width=850,height=550)
m7=folium.Map(location=[y_mean, x_mean],zoom_start=12)
fig7.add_child(m7)
HeatMapWithTime(lat_long_list,radius=5,auto_play=True,position='bottomright', index = list(range(1997,2021))).add_to(m7)
m7

5.1.2 Insights From The Heatmap

The heatmap is fully interactive and each reader can draw their own insight from them. But here are some examples that we thought were interesting:

  • Eventhough the most trees were planted in 1998 (seen from previous barplots) the most area covered was in 2000
  • 1998 was also the year were most of the trees were planted in parks.
  • Not only has the amount of trees planted been decreased since 2000, but the distribution is less dense than what is seen before.

5.2 Diversity By Area

A lack of species diversity can leave the trees vulnerable to threats from pests, disease, and stress due to climate change. Diversification is a basic rule for reducing risk and a greater range of species will provide greater resilience and long-term stability for the tree areas.
So we will now look into how diverse 6 of the city areas in melbourne are.

df3 = data.groupby(["Genus"])['CoM ID'].nunique().nlargest(20)

top_genus = list(df3.keys())

data3 = data[data['Genus'].isin(top_genus)].reset_index()

df4=data3.groupby(["Genus","Area"])['CoM ID'].nunique()

data4 = data3.pivot_table(values="index", index=['Area'], columns='Genus',aggfunc=lambda x: len(x.unique()))
data4 = data4.fillna(0)
